                        <foliation>The manuscript is foliated with the numbers 1-14, in pencil, in Arabic
                  numerals, recto, upper right.</foliation>

                        <collation>
                           <p>This part consists of parts of 34 quires, of which the only one to survive in
                    full is a quaternion.</p>
                           <p>
                              <list>
                                 <item>Quire 1<hi rend="superscript">8-4</hi>
                                    <locus from="1r" to="4v"> ff. 1-4 </locus>
                                    <note>This was probably a quaternion, from which the first, second, seventh
                          and eighth folios have been lost.</note>
                                 </item>
                                 <item>Quire 2<hi rend="superscript">8-7</hi>
                                    <locus from="5r" to="5v"> f. 5 </locus>
                                    <note>This is the first folio of an otherwise lost quire.</note>
                                 </item>
                                 <item>Quire 3<hi rend="superscript">8-7</hi>
                                    <locus from="5r" to="6v"> ff. 5-6 </locus>
                                    <note>This is the single surviving folio of an otherwise lost quire.</note>
                                 </item>
                                 <item>Quire 4<hi rend="superscript">8</hi>
                                    <locus from="7r" to="14v"> ff. 7-14 </locus>
                                    <note>This quire survives in full, though the first and last folios are
                          detached.</note>
                                 </item>
                              </list>
                           </p>
                           <signatures type="quire">There are quire signatures in Greek numerals on ff.
                      <locus from="5r" to="5r">5r</locus> and <locus from="7r" to="7r">7r</locus>,
                    recto, upper right, giving the numbers 6 and 21 respectively (ϛʹ,
                    καʹ).</signatures>
                        </collation>

                        <condition>A small area from the lower inner corner of <locus from="6r" to="14v">ff.
                    6-14</locus> is torn away and there are occasional small tears from the edges
                  elsewhere, and some small holes. Much of the paint and gold leaf of the miniatures
                  has been lost to abrasion. There is also abrasion of the ink, which has been
                  overwritten in places with black ink. There is some creasing, areas of dirt and
                  water staining, extensively on <locus from="14r" to="14v">f.
                  14r-14v</locus>.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>

                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" rulingMedium="hardpoint" topLine="below" writtenLines="25">A
                  single column of 25 lines. <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height quantity="185">185</height>
                              <width quantity="120">120</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <seg type="pricking">Pricking survives in the lower margin, but most has been lost
                    to cropping.</seg>
                           <seg type="ruling">Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy <formula notation="Leroy">32C1</formula>. Text hangs from the lines.</seg>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>

                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="sole" xml:id="hand-1">
                        <p>The main text was copied in a scribal <term type="script">mixed minuscule
                    script</term>, slanting to the right, in brown ink. The size of letters is
                  generally consistent, with occasional expansions.</p>
                        <p>Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear only at the end of
                  lines, and are uncommon even there, except for the use of a horizontal line for
                    <hi rend="italic">nu</hi>. Breathings are both angular and round, and mute <hi rend="italic">iota</hi> is either adscript or in a transitional position below
                  and to the right of the letter. Use of the double dot is functional only,
                  appearing as two short vertical strokes rather than dots. There is accentuation of
                  all lengths of <foreign xml:lang="la">nomina sacra</foreign>. The double grave
                  accent is in use. <foreign xml:lang="la">Nomina sacra</foreign> strokes are
                  sometimes decorated with two vertical strokes.</p>
                        <p>Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points and the lower and middle
                  commas.</p>
                        <p>Captions to miniatures are written in <term type="script">Alexandrine
                    majuscule</term> script in red ink.</p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>

                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="miniature">The text is provided with numerous miniatures illustrating
                the narrative, in gold and red, blue, brown, black, grey, white, magenta, green and
                pink paint. These appear on ff. <locus from="2r" to="2r">2r</locus>, <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v</locus>, <locus from="4v" to="4v">4v</locus>, <locus from="5v" to="7r">5v-7r</locus>, <locus from="9r" to="9v">9r-9v</locus>, <locus from="13v" to="13v">13v</locus> and <locus from="14v" to="14v">14v</locus>.</decoNote>

                     <decoNote type="colInit">The beginnings of sections are marked by simple minor
                initials in red ink.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>

                  <additions>
                     <p>There are occasional pen-trials.</p>
                     <p>Notes in pencil have been added in the margins, giving column references to the
                text in the <hi rend="italic">Patrologia Graeca</hi>.</p>
                  </additions>

                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding>
                        <p>ff. <locus from="1r" to="4v">1-4</locus> and <locus from="8r" to="13v">8-13</locus> remain stitched. The stitching of <locus from="8r" to="13v">ff.
                    8-13</locus> appears early, that of <locus from="1r" to="4v">ff. 1-4</locus>
                  later.</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>

                  <accMat>The manuscript is accompanied by two handwritten notes on card, one concerning
              the collation and the other the content and dating of this manuscript and <bibl subtype="internal" type="MS">MS Add. 4492</bibl>.</accMat>
               </physDesc>

               <history>
                  <origin>The manuscript from which the fragment came, the now lost <bibl subtype="external" type="MS">Ioannina, Zosimaia Bibliotheke, MS 1</bibl>, was probably
              produced in <placeName key="place_g">Cyprus</placeName> in the <origDate calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1149" notBefore="1050">second half of the 11th or first half of the 12th
                century</origDate>, as suggested by the style of script and miniatures.</origin>

                  <provenance>
                     <p>The main body of the manuscript to which this fragment originally belonged was owned in by the Durachani Monastery near Ioannina, and
                transferred in <date calendar="gregorian" when="1846-05-04">1846</date> to the
                Zosimaia Schole in Ioannina. It is unclear whether or not these folios had become
                separated from it at this time.</p>
                     <p>These folios were probably acquired in a collection of manuscripts bought from a
                dealer in <placeName key="place_v7011082">Ioannina</placeName> in <date calendar="gregorian" when="1870">1870</date> for <name key="person_v315943940" role="fmo" type="person">
                           <persName type="display">Baroness Angela Burdett-Coutts
                    (1814-1906)</persName>
                           <persName type="standard">Burdett-Coutts, Angela Georgina,
                    1814-1906</persName>
                        </name>.</p>
                     <p>Probably bought from Burdett-Coutts by <name key="person_v75300714" role="fmo" type="person">
                           <persName type="display">Frederick H.A. Scrivener
                    (1813-1891)</persName>
                           <persName type="standard">Scrivener, Frederick Henry
                    Ambrose, 1813-1891</persName>
                        </name>.</p>
                  </provenance>

                  <acquisition calendar="gregorian" when="1909">Purchased by the University Library in
              1909 from Scrivener's daughter <name role="fmo" type="person">
                        <persName type="display">Frances Emily Scrivener</persName>
                        <persName type="standard">Scrivener, Frances
                  Emily</persName>
                     </name>.</acquisition>
               </history>

